# React Component Conventions

## TypeScript

- All component props must have explicit `interface` definitions
- All event handlers must have proper types
- Generic components must use proper TypeScript generics
- Never use `any` for props -- define exact shapes

```typescript
interface ButtonProps {
  onClick: () => void
  children: React.ReactNode
  variant?: 'default' | 'outline' | 'destructive'
  disabled?: boolean
}
```

## Component Design

- Every component must handle all states: loading, error, empty, and data
- All interactive elements must be keyboard accessible
- All images must have alt text
- All icon buttons must have `aria-label`
- Color contrast must meet WCAG AA (4.5:1)
- Focus indicators must be visible
- Use semantic HTML (`<button>`, `<nav>`, `<main>`)

## Styling

- Use Tailwind CSS utilities, never inline styles
- Use `cn()` utility for conditional class composition
- Use `cva()` (class-variance-authority) for variant patterns
- Use design tokens (CSS variables) for colors -- no hardcoded hex values in components
- Mobile-first responsive design (start with mobile, enhance with `md:`, `lg:`)
- Touch targets must be at least 44x44px
- No horizontal scrolling on mobile

## State Handling

```typescript
// Always handle all states
if (isLoading) return <Skeleton />
if (error) return <Alert variant="destructive">{error.message}</Alert>
if (!data.length) return <EmptyState />
return <DataList data={data} />
```

## Forms

- Validate all inputs with Zod + `zodResolver` from `@hookform/resolvers`
- Use `react-hook-form` for form state management
- Display clear validation error messages
- Show loading states during submission
- Sanitize user input -- never use `dangerouslySetInnerHTML` without `DOMPurify`

## Performance

- Use `React.memo()` for expensive re-rendering components
- Use `useMemo()` for expensive calculations
- Use `useCallback()` for handlers passed to memoized children
- Lazy load heavy components with `next/dynamic`
- Avoid inline function definitions in JSX
